b"@laurencetratt that's fair then. I think len(x) gets discussed all the time whereas the pattern is found everywhere in Python."
b'@laurencetratt do you also consider as warts: callable(x) (x.__call__), str(x) (x.__str__), repr(x) (x.__repr__) etc? Same pattern.'
b'@laurencetratt which basically says: by convention, implement __len__ on x and you can use len(x). That\'s fair and no guesses for "size" etc'
b'@laurencetratt if x can be used for len(x), at least everyone knows where to look (for the code) to determine the size of the object'
b"@laurencetratt so the approach is complementary to classes and inheritance, it's not one way or the other."
b'@laurencetratt the global functions only apply when a class implements the method(s) that the global function expects.'
b"@laurencetratt for example, inheriting from Python's collection of base classes also modifies isinstance checks to do the right thing."
b"@laurencetratt while Python's type system isn't great, the idea that you can get the size of x by calling len(x) is quite nice."
b'@laurencetratt what if a library is released that uses "length" or other names? Then nothing is enforced, it\'s only by convention.'
